{"title_page": "Kastri, Phocis", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Kastri (disambiguation){{!}}Kastri}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name = Kastri Village\n| native_name = \u039a\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03af \n| coordinates = {{Coord|38.4812634|N|22.5016871|E|type:landmark_region:GR_scale:4000|}}\n| location = [[Phocis]], Greece\n| image = Ancient_Village_of_Kastri.jpg\n| caption = Village of Kastri before the Delphi excavation\n| region = [[Central Greece]]\n| abandoned = 1893\n| cultures = [[Byzantine Greece|Medieval Greece]]\n| archaeologists = [[William Martin Leake]]\n| notes = \n}}\n\n'''Kastri''' was a medieval village in Greece, which was formed above the ruins of the ancient site of [[Delphi]]. The local villagers partly used the ruins in the construction of their village. The village was destroyed during the exploratory archaeological digging for the ancient site of Delphi in late 19th century.\n\n== History ==\nThe temple and statues at Delphi were destroyed under the rule of Theodosius I in c. 390 AD. The village of Kastri was built on top of the ruins using marble from destroyed buildings and, eventually, the precise location of Delphi was lost.<ref name=lawton1889>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gWEZAAAAYAAJ|title=Delphi, the Locality and Its Legends|last=Lawton|first=William Cranston|year=1889|page=808}}</ref>\n\nGeorge Wheeler and Jacques Spon rediscovered the site using an old description from [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], and published their findings in 1682.<ref name=lawton1889 /> Other explorers noted the remains of the ancient temple in Kastri, including Colonel [[William Martin Leake]] who visited the site in 1802 and 1806.<ref name=gagarin2009>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lNV6-HsUppsC|title=Ancient Greece and Rome|last=Gagarin|first=Michael|date=31 December 2009|publisher=Oxford University Press, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-19-517072-6|page=386}}</ref> In 1838, Greek scholars suggested that the village be moved to allow excavation of the site. In 1891, the [[French Archaeological School of Athens]] pledged a sum of money to facilitate the removal of the villagers to the site of the modern city of Delphi and, in return, was granted a ten-year concession to excavate the site.<ref name=gagarin2009/> The village was estimated to consist of about one hundred homes and two hundred inhabitants.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7YckKxHBpEcC|title=The Oracle: Ancient Delphi and the Science Behind Its Lost Secrets|last=Broad|first=William J.|date=2007-01-30|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4406-4934-9}}</ref> \n\nDuring the excavation, the French Archaeologists removed vast quantities of soil from landslides that had covered the major buildings and structures of Delphi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Delphi |url=http://www.culture.gr/2/21/211/21110a/e211ja01.html |website=Hellenic Ministry of Culture |accessdate=30 April 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050401090258/http://www.culture.gr/2/21/211/21110a/e211ja01.html |archivedate= 1 April 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe new village that was created for the inhabitants of Kastri is now part of modern-day Delphi, and the name is not used locally anymore.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Delphi Archaeological Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Delphi]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Greece]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Kastri (disambiguation){{!}}Kastri}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name = Kastri Village\n| native_name = \u039a\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03af \n| coordinates = {{Coord|38.4812634|N|22.5016871|E|type:landmark_region:GR_scale:4000|}}\n| location = [[Phocis]], Greece\n| image = Ancient_Village_of_Kastri.jpg\n| caption = Village of Kastri before the Delphi excavation\n| region = [[Central Greece]]\n| abandoned = 1893\n| cultures = [[Byzantine Greece|Medieval Greece]]\n| archaeologists = \n| notes = \n}}\n\n'''Kastri''' was a medieval village in Greece, which was formed above the ruins of the ancient site of [[Delphi]]. The local villagers partly used the ruins in the construction of their village. The village was destroyed during the exploratory archaeological digging for the ancient site of Delphi in late 19th century.\n\n== History ==\nThe temple and statues at Delphi were destroyed under the rule of Theodosius I in c. 390 AD. The village of Kastri was built on top of the ruins using marble from destroyed buildings and, eventually, the precise location of Delphi was lost.<ref name=lawton1889>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gWEZAAAAYAAJ|title=Delphi, the Locality and Its Legends|last=Lawton|first=William Cranston|year=1889|page=808}}</ref>\n\nGeorge Wheeler and Jacques Spon rediscovered the site using an old description from [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], and published their findings in 1682.<ref name=lawton1889 /> Other explorers noted the remains of the ancient temple in Kastri, including Colonel [[William Martin Leake]] who visited the site in 1802 and 1806.<ref name=gagarin2009>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lNV6-HsUppsC|title=Ancient Greece and Rome|last=Gagarin|first=Michael|date=31 December 2009|publisher=Oxford University Press, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-19-517072-6|page=386}}</ref> In 1838, Greek scholars suggested that the village be moved to allow excavation of the site. In 1891, the [[French Archaeological School of Athens]] pledged a sum of money to facilitate the removal of the villagers to the site of the modern city of Delphi and, in return, was granted a ten-year concession to excavate the site.<ref name=gagarin2009/> The village was estimated to consist of about one hundred homes and two hundred inhabitants.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7YckKxHBpEcC|title=The Oracle: Ancient Delphi and the Science Behind Its Lost Secrets|last=Broad|first=William J.|date=2007-01-30|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4406-4934-9}}</ref> \n\nDuring the excavation, the French Archaeologists removed vast quantities of soil from landslides that had covered the major buildings and structures of Delphi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Delphi |url=http://www.culture.gr/2/21/211/21110a/e211ja01.html |website=Hellenic Ministry of Culture |accessdate=30 April 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050401090258/http://www.culture.gr/2/21/211/21110a/e211ja01.html |archivedate= 1 April 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe new village that was created for the inhabitants of Kastri is now part of modern-day Delphi, and the name is not used locally anymore.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Delphi Archaeological Museum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Delphi]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Greece]]\n", "name_user": "Jaycangel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added William Martin Leake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kastri,_Phocis"}
